comments: Dinwiddie (DAL) is bracing for the contact from Conley (UTA) and marginal contact occurs as Dinwiddie releases from the contact.
Conley (UTA) is retreating his arm into a vertical position and absorbs the marginal contact from Dinwiddie (DAL) during his driving shot attempt.
Bullock (DAL) places his hand momentarily on Clarkson's (UTA) hip and marginal contact occurs as they move in the same direction.
Clarkson (UTA) is already in Dinwiddie's (DAL) path and marginal contact occurs as the defenders switch.
Doncic (DAL) is in the paint for less than three seconds when he moves to imminently guard an opponent.
Sexton (UTA) momentarily grasps Kleber's (DAL) left arm and marginal contact occurs during the drive.
Kleber (DAL) applies his forearm to Sexton's (UTA) side and marginal contact occurs during the driving shot attempt.
Conley (UTA) legally contests Doncic's (DAL) jump shot attempt.
Markkanen (UTA) brings his hand towards Bullock (DAL) and marginal contact occurs as he releases from the contact.
Doncic (DAL) is retreating his arms to a vertical position and marginal contact occurs as he defends Markkanen's (UTA) shot near the rim.
Bullock (DAL) is already in Vanderbilt's (UTA) path when contact occurs and he does not deliver contact.
Dinwiddie (DAL) is already in Vanderbilt's (UTA) path as he moves his forearm slightly forward towards Vanderbilt, and marginal contact occurs during the pick.

As Dinwiddie (DAL) releases away from Sexton (UTA), his hand brushes Sexton's head/face and some contact occurs.   Contact to an opponent's head/face can be deemed marginal when the result of a natural basketball move, provided the contact is not disproportionate or uncontrolled.
Dinwiddie (DAL) momentarily brings a hand to Clarkson's (UTA) back while releasing away, and marginal contact occurs during the drive.
Dinwiddie (DET) extends his arm into Sexton's (UTA) path and initiates contact that affects Sexton's FOM during the inbound.
Kleber (DAL) legally contests Clarkson's (UTA) jump shot attempt. Any "high-five" contact after the release is considered incidental.
Clarkson's (UTA) right leg naturally drifts forward during his jump shot attempt, and he avoids initiating contact with Kleber (DAL) during his jump shot attempt.
Finney-Smith (DAL) makes clean contact with the ball, and any ensuing arm contact with Beasley's (UTA) arm is considered marginal.
